WEBVTT

00:00.521 --> 00:03.128
So here's what you missed
<i>on</i> Glee: <i>A gun went off</i>

00:03.137 --> 00:04.781
<i>at school and everyone</i>
<i>was terrified,</i>

00:04.789 --> 00:07.034
<i>and Sue said it was hers</i>
<i>and had to leave McKinley,</i>

00:07.052 --> 00:11.379
I'm ready to take my punishment. <i>But
secretly she's just protecting Becky.</i>

00:11.381 --> 00:13.097
Emma, stop. Stop.
<i>Finn kissed Emma</i>

00:13.099 --> 00:15.066
<i>and then apologized to Will,</i>
<i>I'm so sorry.</i>

00:15.068 --> 00:17.394
<i>But Will never really forgave</i>
<i>him so Finn went off to college</i>

00:17.403 --> 00:19.370
<i>to fulfill his dream</i>
<i>of becoming a teacher.</i>

00:19.372 --> 00:21.405
Broadwayworld.com is saying
<i>Funny Girl</i> is finally

00:21.407 --> 00:23.374
happening this season.
<i>And Rachel got an audition</i>

00:23.376 --> 00:26.044
<i>to play Fanny Brice in a</i>
<i>Broadway revival of</i> Funny Girl,

00:26.046 --> 00:27.578
<i>to fulfill her dream of playing</i>
<i>Fanny Brice</i>

00:27.580 --> 00:29.364
<i>in a Broadway production</i>
<i>of</i> Funny Girl.

00:29.366 --> 00:31.633
<i>And that's what you missed</i>
<i>on</i> Glee.

00:32.213 --> 00:34.380
FINN: <i>The truth is, I decided to
go to the Army after high school</i>

00:34.431 --> 00:37.466
<i>because I was kind of</i>
<i>afraid of college.</i>

00:37.500 --> 00:39.601
<i>Smart people go to college,</i>
<i>like doctors.</i>

00:39.636 --> 00:42.888
<i>The whole thing just seemed</i>
<i>scarier than getting shot.</i>

00:42.939 --> 00:44.807
<i>But now that I'm here</i>
<i>at</i> the <i>University of Lima,</i>

00:44.841 --> 00:46.692
<i>I wish I would've come sooner.</i>

00:46.726 --> 00:49.395
<i>I'm studying to be a teacher,</i>
<i>something I love,</i>

00:49.446 --> 00:51.563
<i>and that makes the work</i>
<i>not feel like work.</i>

00:51.648 --> 00:53.849
♪ Con los terroristas

00:53.867 --> 00:56.402
♪

00:56.453 --> 00:57.903
♪ Then do the Harlem Shake

00:57.954 --> 01:00.656
<i>And everywhere you go,</i>

01:00.690 --> 01:02.908
<i>even inside classrooms</i>
<i>and study halls,</i>

01:02.959 --> 01:04.376
<i>people find a way to have fun.</i>

01:04.411 --> 01:05.878
♪ Con los terroristas.

01:05.912 --> 01:08.464
(indistinct chatter)
(lion growls)

01:08.498 --> 01:11.049
<i>College is like this perfect</i>
<i>little bubble between</i>

01:11.084 --> 01:13.135
<i>being a kid and being an adult.</i>

01:13.169 --> 01:15.587
♪ Con los terroristas

01:15.638 --> 01:17.673
♪

01:17.707 --> 01:18.974
♪ Then do the Harlem Shake

01:19.008 --> 01:21.310
(indistinct chatter, whooping)

01:21.344 --> 01:23.512
♪ Ey

01:25.815 --> 01:27.316
♪ Con los terroristas.

01:27.350 --> 01:29.151
(lion growls)

01:29.185 --> 01:30.652
<i>And I've got the rest</i>
<i>of my li to be a grown-up.</i>

01:30.687 --> 01:33.322
♪ (cheering, whooping)

01:33.356 --> 01:35.073
<i>And for now,</i>

01:35.108 --> 01:36.725
<i>it's okay to be young.</i>

01:36.743 --> 01:38.243
(lion growls)

01:38.278 --> 01:39.661
(cheering)

01:41.080 --> 01:42.247
Hey.

01:42.949 --> 01:43.832
Get up.

01:43.867 --> 01:45.951
(zipper opens)

01:46.002 --> 01:47.068
Puck!
(shouts)

01:47.120 --> 01:48.253
What are you doing here?

01:48.288 --> 01:49.755
I live here now.
What?

01:49.789 --> 01:51.239
(shouts, chuckles)

01:51.257 --> 01:53.175
Which dorm?
This one.

01:53.209 --> 01:55.427
Like, right here. Top bunk.
Wh-What happened to Lee Hei?

01:55.462 --> 01:57.262
Hei's no longer. He moved out
a couple hours ago.

01:57.297 --> 01:59.431
I told him if he hoped to get
any studying done this year,

01:59.466 --> 02:01.266
he should probably find another room.
I-I can't believe

02:01.301 --> 02:03.135
you're going here. What
are you taking? Taking?

02:03.186 --> 02:04.419
You mean, like, classes?

02:04.437 --> 02:06.188
Dude, I'm just here
for my bro, some brews

02:06.222 --> 02:07.606
and the bountiful Bettys.

02:07.640 --> 02:08.590
I love college!

02:08.608 --> 02:09.640
Yeah, college!

02:09.692 --> 02:11.326
(both shouting)

02:11.360 --> 02:14.277
<font color="#40bfff">Sync & corrections by <font color="#FFA500">wilson0804</font></font>
<font color="#40bfff">www.Addic7ed.com</font>

02:14.397 --> 02:15.898
RACHEL: <i>Some dreams are bigger</i>
<i>than others.</i>

02:15.932 --> 02:18.150
<i>Me being on Broadway,</i>
<i>that's a big dream.</i>

02:18.201 --> 02:21.403
<i>Me being on Broadway</i>
<i>in</i> Funny Girl <i>as Fanny Brice,</i>

02:21.437 --> 02:23.705
<i>inheriting the mantle</i>
<i>of my idol,</i>

02:23.740 --> 02:27.275
<i>Ms. Barbra Streisand,</i>
<i>that's the culmination</i>

02:27.293 --> 02:29.578
<i>of every dream I've ever had.</i>

02:29.612 --> 02:31.997
<i>Since its premiere in 1964,</i>
Funny Girl <i>has never</i>

02:32.048 --> 02:33.665
<i>been revived on Broadway...</i>
<i>no doubt because</i>

02:33.716 --> 02:35.634
<i>producers haven't been able</i>
<i>to find</i>

02:35.668 --> 02:38.303
<i>an actress capable of filling</i>
<i>Barbra's formidable shoes.</i>

02:38.338 --> 02:41.306
<i>Luckily, I've been grooming</i>
<i>myself for this audition</i>

02:41.341 --> 02:43.642
<i>since I was five,</i>
<i>which is when I first</i>

02:43.676 --> 02:47.246
<i>saw</i> Funny Girl <i>in all</i>
<i>its Technicolor glory.</i>

02:47.280 --> 02:49.314
<i>I heard my dads use the phrase</i>
<i>"star quality" before,</i>

02:49.349 --> 02:53.318
<i>but I never truly understood it</i>
<i>until that moment.</i>

02:53.353 --> 02:56.071
<i>I knew: I needed to be her.</i>

02:56.105 --> 02:59.324
<i>From that point on, it's been</i>
<i>all Barbra, all the time.</i>

02:59.359 --> 03:01.994
<i>Witness my collection:</i>
<i>A feather from</i> Hello, Dolly!;

03:02.028 --> 03:04.496
<i>A yarmulke from</i> Yentl; <i>a boxing</i>
<i>glove from</i> The Main Event;

03:04.531 --> 03:08.333
<i>Signed Playbills; a picture</i>
<i>of her first husband,</i>

03:08.368 --> 03:10.786
<i>Mr. Elliott Gould;</i>
<i>Her second husband,</i>

03:10.820 --> 03:12.421
<i>Mr. James Brolin;</i>
<i>And her paramour</i>

03:12.455 --> 03:14.840
<i>of two years, Canadian</i>
<i>Prime Minister Pierre Trudeau.</i>

03:14.874 --> 03:17.843
<i>But I'm not just approaching</i>
<i>this audition as a fangirl.</i>

03:17.927 --> 03:19.711
<i>I'm approaching this</i>
<i>as a professional</i>

03:19.762 --> 03:21.547
<i>who has sworn off men</i>

03:21.598 --> 03:24.132
<i>and rededicated herself</i>
<i>to the art of being Barbra.</i>

03:24.166 --> 03:26.134
<i>Yes, it's a long shot.</i>

03:26.168 --> 03:29.054
<i>Fanny Brice is the King Lear</i>
<i>of musical theatre roles,</i>

03:29.105 --> 03:31.607
<i>and I'm just an unknown</i>
<i>Jewish girl from Ohio,</i>

03:31.641 --> 03:33.942
<i>who came of the age</i>
<i>in a high school glee club.</i>

03:33.977 --> 03:35.527
<i>But then I remind myself,</i>

03:35.562 --> 03:37.563
<i>Barbra, too, was once</i>
<i>an unknown Jewish girl</i>

03:37.614 --> 03:39.114
<i>who sang</i>
<i>in her high school choir.</i>

03:39.148 --> 03:41.199
<i>And</i> Funny Girl <i>made her a star.</i>

03:41.234 --> 03:43.702
<i>So why can't my dreams</i>
<i>come true, too?</i>

03:43.736 --> 03:46.154
Hello, gorgeous.

03:46.188 --> 03:48.624
ROZ: Excuse my jet lag,
I'm fresh off a plane

03:48.658 --> 03:50.709
from North Korea
where I've been training

03:50.743 --> 03:53.045
their swim team with
my assistant Dennis Rodman.

03:53.079 --> 03:54.796
Do you like the new addition
to my wardrobe?

03:54.831 --> 03:56.632
That's right. I've taken over
the Cheerios!

03:56.666 --> 03:58.383
From that Phantom Menace
Sue Sylvester.

03:58.418 --> 04:00.302
Someone with talent had to.

04:00.336 --> 04:01.670
Did I also mention
that I'm in talks

04:01.704 --> 04:03.505
with Miss Oprah Winfrey

04:03.539 --> 04:06.174
to launch my very own
Cheerio! Network?

04:06.208 --> 04:08.560
Like George Jefferson,
I'm movin' on up.

04:08.595 --> 04:10.896
How is your delicate group
of weirdos? Are they still

04:10.930 --> 04:12.714
rattled by that fake
school shooting?

04:12.732 --> 04:14.733
That was a terrifying experience
for those kids.

04:14.767 --> 04:17.069
And the adults.
I'm still having nightmares.

04:17.103 --> 04:18.987
Honey, please.
I'm a child of the ghetto.

04:19.022 --> 04:22.024
I can't sleep at night unless
I hear at least two gunshots.

04:23.109 --> 04:24.743
Hey.

04:24.777 --> 04:26.745
You get a chance
to talk to Finn yet?

04:26.779 --> 04:29.498
No. I'm not ready.
Will, come on.

04:29.532 --> 04:31.066
You need to patch the hole
in this fence

04:31.117 --> 04:32.668
so the squirrels don't escape.

04:32.702 --> 04:34.920
People grow apart, Shannon.
That's life.

04:34.954 --> 04:36.922
Th-There's nothing wrong
with that.

04:36.956 --> 04:39.291
That's what I thought about me
and my sister, Denise.

04:39.342 --> 04:42.210
We used to scrap like grizzlies
in the Arctic,

04:42.244 --> 04:43.462
and then when all that stuff

04:43.513 --> 04:44.963
went down with Cooter,

04:45.014 --> 04:46.431
she helped me out,

04:46.466 --> 04:48.133
and we finally got to talkin'.

04:48.184 --> 04:49.935
I'm more stubborn
than anybody here...

04:49.969 --> 04:52.137
(chuckles) but I swallowed hard

04:52.188 --> 04:53.605
and made amends with her.

04:55.191 --> 04:57.893
It was one of the best things
I've ever done in my life.

04:59.646 --> 05:01.763
Make the effort, Will.

05:06.402 --> 05:08.403
It's worth it.

05:11.207 --> 05:12.874
(school bell ringing)

05:12.909 --> 05:15.877
MARLEY: <i>I, Marley Rose,</i>
<i>have made a decision.</i>

05:15.912 --> 05:18.213
<i>I took that false bottom</i>
<i>out of my desk drawer,</i>

05:18.247 --> 05:20.799
<i>and I'm finally going to let</i>
<i>my songs see the light of day.</i>

05:20.833 --> 05:22.884
<i>I want to be like all those</i>
<i>singer-songwriters.</i>

05:22.919 --> 05:26.555
<i>I look up to: Joni Mitchell,</i>
<i>Norah Jones, Chrissie Hynde.</i>

05:26.589 --> 05:28.507
<i>I've been trying</i>
<i>to bring it up with everyone,</i>

05:28.558 --> 05:30.392
<i>but ever since the gun</i>
<i>went off in school,</i>

05:30.426 --> 05:31.810
<i>everyone's been acting strange.</i>

05:31.844 --> 05:33.478
<i>It's like they've all got PTSD.</i>

05:33.513 --> 05:35.647
BRITTANY: They really want me
to study string theory,

05:35.682 --> 05:37.315
but I'm not all that interested
in arts and crafts.

05:37.350 --> 05:39.317
<i>Brittany's acting weird</i>
<i>because M.I.T. found out</i>

05:39.352 --> 05:40.802
<i>about her S.A.T. score,</i>
<i>and they're pressuring her</i>

05:40.820 --> 05:42.320
<i>for early commitment.</i>

05:42.355 --> 05:44.690
Isn't M.I.T in Europe?
That would suck.

05:44.741 --> 05:46.742
Hey, Tina. Are you
trying out a new look?

05:46.809 --> 05:48.910
It's called steampunk.
It's the next big thing.

05:48.945 --> 05:51.113
Oh. God, I love it.

05:51.147 --> 05:52.864
(Australian accent): Oh, hey there.
You must, uh, be Marley.

05:52.915 --> 05:55.000
Hi, Sam. That's not Sam.
That's Sam's

05:55.034 --> 05:56.585
smarter twin brother, Evan.
Evan Evans.

05:56.619 --> 05:57.836
What a pleasure to meet you.

05:57.870 --> 05:59.454
Oh. Phone's ringing.
Oh, it's my brother.

05:59.488 --> 06:03.175
Oh, hey, Sam, I was actually
just looking for you...

06:03.209 --> 06:05.510
So have you guys heard
who's taking over the Cheerios!?

06:05.545 --> 06:07.763
Yeah, it's insane.
And it made me realize

06:07.797 --> 06:10.382
I have no idea whether I'm
on the Cheerios! Or not.

06:10.433 --> 06:12.601
Like, literally can't remember.

06:12.635 --> 06:13.835
Hey, guys.

06:13.853 --> 06:15.303
Have you seen Evan?
You just missed him.

06:15.337 --> 06:16.054
He went that way.

06:16.105 --> 06:17.806
(groans)

06:17.840 --> 06:20.442
<i>I think Sam might have</i>
<i>a little separation anxiety,</i>

06:20.476 --> 06:23.111
<i>so he's pretending</i>
<i>he has a twin. And then...</i>

06:23.146 --> 06:25.814
<i>there's Unique.</i>
Unique, what are you doing?

06:25.848 --> 06:28.533
Are those birth control pills?
Shh!

06:28.568 --> 06:31.453
Don't blow a girl's cover. Kitty hooked
me up with a prescription for Loestrin,

06:31.487 --> 06:33.288
and I heard that two dolls
a day will turn my Bs

06:33.322 --> 06:34.790
into Ds in no time.

06:34.824 --> 06:37.292
Guys, have you...
seen my twin?

06:37.326 --> 06:38.994
Oh! Getting a call.
Hold on.

06:39.028 --> 06:42.664
Oh, hey. Man, I was
just looking for you!

06:42.698 --> 06:44.966
Unique, you cannot
take birth control.

06:45.001 --> 06:46.868
Why not? Trans kids
everywhere are doing it.

06:46.886 --> 06:48.136
All right, bro. Well,
I'll tell 'em you said hi.

06:48.171 --> 06:49.638
Oh, yeah, yeah.
Have fun at the zoo.

06:49.672 --> 06:51.890
<i>I've just got to build up</i>
<i>the courage to tell everyone</i>

06:51.924 --> 06:54.976
<i>that I want us to perform one</i>
<i>of my songs at regionals.</i>

06:55.011 --> 06:56.678
<i>It would be a dream come true.</i>

06:56.712 --> 06:58.897
WILL: Big news, guys.
I just got a direct tweet

06:58.931 --> 07:00.398
from the Greater Midwest
Regional.

07:00.433 --> 07:02.484
High School Show Choir
Board of Directors.

07:02.518 --> 07:03.902
(light cheering)

07:03.936 --> 07:05.904
The theme
for this year's regionals

07:05.938 --> 07:07.989
is...
Sweaters.

07:08.024 --> 07:08.824
...dreams.

07:08.858 --> 07:10.075
(sighs) Close.

07:10.109 --> 07:11.910
As you know,
some of the past judges

07:11.944 --> 07:13.361
we've had haven't been
that bright,

07:13.395 --> 07:14.279
or that sober,

07:14.330 --> 07:15.747
so our best bet is to take

07:15.782 --> 07:17.415
the dream theme literally.

07:17.450 --> 07:19.201
We'll start out
with "Dream Weaver"

07:19.235 --> 07:20.485
and then we'll segue
into "Sweet Dreams"

07:20.520 --> 07:21.837
and we'll bring it home

07:21.871 --> 07:23.421
with "You Make
My Dreams Come True."

07:23.456 --> 07:24.790
Okay.

07:24.841 --> 07:26.591
Marley, you're frowning.

07:26.626 --> 07:28.960
No. I just don't know
any of those songs.

07:29.011 --> 07:30.095
Well, you'll know them
soon enough

07:30.129 --> 07:31.596
because we're learning them
today.

07:31.631 --> 07:32.848
(clears throat) Maybe...

07:32.882 --> 07:35.016
could we try
some original songs,

07:35.051 --> 07:36.601
like you did two years ago?

07:36.636 --> 07:38.053
Yeah, my twin brother Sam
told me you guys

07:38.087 --> 07:39.638
totally crushed
regionals two years ago

07:39.689 --> 07:40.722
with those sweet tunes.

07:40.756 --> 07:42.390
Well, S... um, Evan,

07:42.424 --> 07:44.693
that was a different time
and a different team.

07:44.727 --> 07:47.863
Mr. Shue, could we at least talk
about the set list?

07:47.897 --> 07:49.698
I mean, when Finn was here,
we got to help...

07:49.732 --> 07:51.399
Do I have to remind you guys
how lucky we are

07:51.433 --> 07:52.701
to even be at regionals?

07:52.735 --> 07:54.202
We're there on a technicality,

07:54.237 --> 07:55.570
which means there's absolutely

07:55.604 --> 07:58.123
no room for even
the smallest of mistakes.

07:58.157 --> 08:00.292
Trust me.

08:00.326 --> 08:01.626
Anybody else have something
they want to say?

08:01.661 --> 08:04.412
Great. Brad, warm 'em up.

08:08.083 --> 08:09.283
(school bell ringing)
As honorary Rachel,

08:09.317 --> 08:11.001
I would like to convene

08:11.036 --> 08:12.419
this secret meeting
of the glee club.

08:12.454 --> 08:13.954
Oh. Sam's sorry
he couldn't make it.

08:13.988 --> 08:15.322
He said
to tell every... Oh.

08:15.340 --> 08:17.174
Just got a text.

08:17.209 --> 08:19.009
He's here.

08:19.044 --> 08:20.261
Oh, hey, Sam.
Hey, Evan.

08:20.295 --> 08:22.496
How long are we gonna
let him do this?

08:22.514 --> 08:24.131
Just let it go.

08:24.165 --> 08:25.933
It's like waking a sleepwalker.
It might kill him.

08:25.967 --> 08:27.685
Hey, guys. Sorry I'm
late. What'd I miss?

08:27.719 --> 08:29.470
What you missed
was Mr. Shue's set list.

08:29.504 --> 08:30.804
It's gonna lose us regionals.

08:30.838 --> 08:32.606
Oh, yeah, Evan was saying
something about that.

08:32.640 --> 08:36.110
"Dream Weaver." Great song,
but it's from 1975.

08:36.144 --> 08:37.861
"Sweet Dreams (Are Made
of This)." Amazing.

08:37.895 --> 08:39.363
Released in 1982.

08:39.397 --> 08:40.847
"You Make My Dreams Come True."

08:40.865 --> 08:42.316
Originally performed in 1981,

08:42.350 --> 08:43.734
and then performed again
by the glee club in a mash-up

08:43.784 --> 08:45.569
that we did last year,

08:45.620 --> 08:46.870
which Mr. Shue
didn't even remember.

08:46.905 --> 08:48.289
He's completely lost touch.

08:48.323 --> 08:49.957
We're screwed.
Can I get a witness?

08:49.991 --> 08:51.158
We need to do current songs,

08:51.192 --> 08:53.360
and if we do,
I know we can win.

08:53.378 --> 08:54.962
(clears throat) Uh, guys...

08:54.996 --> 08:56.547
can I say something?

08:56.581 --> 08:58.882
I wrote some songs.
What if we performed those?

08:58.917 --> 09:02.052
Please. No one wants to hear a
song about a fat mom. Okay.

09:02.087 --> 09:04.004
What about...
Or a song about barfing.

09:04.038 --> 09:06.390
But what about a song... Or a
song about loving an octoroon.

09:06.424 --> 09:08.676
BLAINE: All right, all
right, all right, let's...

09:08.710 --> 09:10.978
let's get serious.
We need to start brainstorming.

09:11.012 --> 09:13.213
We'll pick a new set list
and then we'll break the news

09:13.231 --> 09:15.733
(bell ringing)
to Mr. Shue.

09:15.767 --> 09:19.386
(Wagner's "Ride
of the Valkyries" playing)

09:22.941 --> 09:25.442
(students chanting):
Go! Go! Go! Go! Go! Go!

09:25.493 --> 09:26.827
(neck cracks)

09:26.861 --> 09:29.730
(knuckles crack)

09:30.582 --> 09:32.082
(cheering, whooping)

09:32.117 --> 09:33.834
(Puck shouts)

09:33.868 --> 09:35.402
(cheering, whooping)

09:35.420 --> 09:37.421
(sizzling)

09:37.455 --> 09:39.423
Excuse me, ladies.
Where are your tickets?

09:39.457 --> 09:40.791
Wait, we need tickets?

09:40.842 --> 09:42.009
Rules are rules.

09:42.043 --> 09:43.844
Wait, wait, wait.

09:43.878 --> 09:45.546
You both seem
like really nice girls,

09:45.580 --> 09:47.014
